example.p:
Using the initial amount of pollutant and letting t represent the time in hours since her first measurement,
she writes

  P(t)=4890(0.96)^{\frac{t}{72}}

We know that in 5 hours the population will grow from 300 to 600.
Therefore,

  300*b^{5}=600
  b^{5}=\frac{600}{300}
  b^{5}=2
  b=2^{\frac{1}{5}}
  b \approx 1.1487

so our formula is P(t) \approx 300(1.1487)^{t}

On the other hand, if you can speak math,
you can write a formula in about two seconds:

  P(t)=300(2)^{\frac{t}{5}}

assemblage.p:
When continuous compounding occurs,
the general formula we came up with earlier

  A_{0}(1+\frac{r}{n})^{nt}

changes form.
It becomes

  A_{0}e^{rt}

